title: For Sale:  Brand New FNH FS-9
postcontent:
The FNS™-9 is the latest handgun innovation by FN Herstal.

The FNS™-9 pistol features a pre-loaded striker mechanism and a manual safety, hence combining fast and accurate shooting and optimal safety.

Additionally, the well thought out design of the FNS™-9 results in a stable, highly ergonomic and ambidextrous pistol that is easy to operate.

Fast and Accurate Shooting


The pre-loaded striker mechanism of the pistol means that energy has been pre-loaded partially. This ensures a short and light trigger pull identical for all shots allowing fast and accurate shooting.

The FNS™-9 has a low bore axis providing minimized perceived recoil and reducing muzzle rise for a perfect weapon controllability.


The handgun features a newly designed three-dot combat sights with deep rear sight notch which improved significantly the accuracy.

Maximized Safety Systems

In addition to the manual safety, the FNS™-9 features Four Major Safeties:

Trigger Safety
Firing Pin Safety
Drop Safety
Out-of-Battery Safety
1. Trigger Safety

The two-piece trigger prevents the weapon from firing without a presure on the trigger.
The rear of lower trigger piece catches on the frame if the mechanism is moved without pulling the trigger.


2. Firing Pin Safety

The firing pin safety prevents the striker from passing.
The firing pin safety is lifted out the way when the trigger is pulled.

 3. Drop Safety

Part of the fire control housing prevents the sear from rotating down to release the stricker unless the trigger is pulled.

 4. Out-of-Battery Safety

When the slide is not fully forwards the sear cannot release the stricker even if the trigger is pulled.

Enhanced Ergonomics

The FNS™-9 pistol comes standard with a large number of ergonomic features such as:
- Ultra nonslip checkered grips for better prehension
- Front serrations for easy press check
- Three interchangeable backstrap inserts quickly adapt to the pistol to the shooter's hand size.


For Right- and Left-Handers

All operating controls are fully ambidextrous:
- Slide stop
- Magazine catch
- Manual safety


Durability and Unequalled Reliability

The pistol features a 4'' hammer-forged stainless steel barrel and ultra-hard coating on stainless steel slide and barrel.

The high quality material is fully tested and fired under severe conditions prior to dispatch.

The pistol accepts all military and law enforcement duty ammunition.

title: For Sale:  Desirable factory engraved gold washed deluxe marlin model 1897 rifle
postcontent:
Desirable factory engraved gold washed deluxe marlin model 1897 rifle- serial no. 194633, 22 SLLR cal., 24 inch octagon bbl., gold finish, walnut stock. This is a unique example of a seldom found factory engraved Marlin Model that's was manufactured in 1900.The receiver is finely engraved with scroll patterns with a curly and wavy line border. In addition there is a round panel on the left side with a buck in a wooden scene. A similar type of engraving featured on a model 1897 is pictured and described as a No. 1 engraving in William Brophy's book MARLIN FIREARMS on page 531 and 534. The top barrel flat is marked with the two line "THE MARLIN FIREARMS CORPORATION/NEW HAVEN CONN. U.S.A. PATENTED". The bottom line is flanked by outward pointing arrows. The upper left rear flat is marked "22 S-L - L-R" flanked by outward pointing arrows and the upper right rear flat is marked with "JM" in an oval. The top of the receiver is engraved "MARLIN SAFETY" with a wavy line border on three sides. The serial number appears on the bottom of the receiver. The barrel is equipped with a dovetail ivory beaded front blade sight and an adjustable rear sporting sight. The upper tang is fitted with a short range Lyman #1 peep sight. Full length magazine tube, all gold washed finish except for blue sights and mounted with a deluxe checkered walnut forearm and pistol grip stock with a crescent buttplate. Information provided by the consignor states that the rifle was shipped from the warehouse on January 15, 1900 with a 24 inch 22 SLLR octagon barrel, full magazine, rifle buttplate, deluxe pistol grip stock and forearm with factory "A" checkering, factory #1 scroll engraved receiver with a deer on the left side with a full nickel finish. The gun was returned to the factory in 1922 and fitted with the Marlins Firearms Corporation barrel and new model 39 coil hammer spring, the latter being first available in 1922. The Marlin firearms Corporation was in existence from 1921 to 1924. The gold wash finish was done when the barrel was replaced. An accompanying Cody Firearms Records Office letter verifies the rifle configuration, caliber, 24 inch octagon barrel, pistol grip stock and shipment on January 15, 1900. Corporation Marlins don't show up every day. Of the few Corporation Marlin's produced, between 1921 and 1924, to be engraved and gold washed is extremely rare and unique. Provenance: Len Guldman Collection, Denver, Colorado.
CONDITION: Fine as factory replated/rebarreled. The rifle retains much of the gold wash finish in protected areas with the original nickel finish visible on the balance. There are a few minor dings on the barrel. The wood is also fine with a small area of gouging on the stock near the toe on the left side, a series of small dents on the dings on the forearm and overall crisp checkering. The markings and engraving are crisp and clear. The action is excellent.

If you are interested please call at REDACTED. Or come on down to 8996 W. Bowles Ave. Unit C-1. Littleton, Co 80123

postcontent: Looking to trade my like new Springfield M1A Socom II for either a LWRC REPR .308, H&K MR 762 or a POF .308 Prefer the 20" barrel but 16" is ok. The M1A with EBR stock is essentially a civilian version of the M14 EBR. Its a M1A socom 2 with a Sage EBR stock. Had the original EBR stock with adjustable butt stock but was way too heavy in comparison to the EBR stock with the M4 butt stock. This stock will accept any M4 / AR-15 stock and most any M4 / AR-15 grip. If not familiar with the Sage EBR stocks look em up and you'll find they are the best M1A chassis bar none. If you have any questions on the stock feel free to ask as I was trained on this weapon platform. The Socom II comes with 16" barrel, tritium inserted factory sights and very nice factory trigger. I installed the Sage EBR stock and outfitted it with a stripper clip mounted picatinny rail, Magpul CTR buttstock and X products 50 round drum (new with box and papers). The pictures show a Surefire 951 weapon light, Urban ERT 2 point hybrid sling, Grip Pod fore grip and Aimpoint COMP M4 but I plan on keeping these. I have about 3200 in this set up without the light, grip, sling and Aimpoint. For the right trade I also have the original black synthetic stock, 10rd Springfield brand mag, about 8 Checkmate industries 20rd mags, 2 Checkmate Industries 25rd mags, replacement mag springs, some magpuls and 4 original Vietnam era GI 20rd Mags (various makers). This rifle has about 200 rounds through it and has been more or a safe queen than I would have liked. It did shoot sub MOA at 100 Meters with a Leupold Mk4 LR/T 3.5-10x40 M5-FF using both Black Hills 175gr SMK HPBT and Lake City Match 175gr BTHP XM118LR. Shot right around MOA at 100 Meters using 175gr Privi Partizan Match HPBT no problem, yet never had a chance to test the 200-600 meter waters. I have a Super Match so this Socom II was mainly intended for tight spaces and under 100M usage, but it sat in safe most of its life. I need an AR type 308 so looking to trade for a LWRC R.E.P.R. 308, HK MR 7.62 or a POF 308 preferring an 20" on the POF and either 20" or 16" on the LWRC R.E.P.R or a scar 308 but length of barrel is not a deal breaker ( I might come up with a real good excuse to purchase the 20" upper if traded for a 16" barrel, lol ) Email or call / text me at 4O4-3I4-SeVen4O7 I can provide additional pics but it will only let me load one due to the size of the pic. title: For Sale:  DILLON XL650 WITH 223 DIES, POWDER, MANY MANY EXTRAS
postcontent:
As I am getting back into aviation, the reloading hobby must go, can't have both.
For sale is my complete Dillon XL650 .223 reloading setup.
I will consider selling just the machine alone, but at this time, please do not offer to buy just the dies or just the powder or just the projectiles.
MORE PHOTOS AT http://s10.photobucket.com/user/helbigtw/library/XL650
--
List of items:
Dillon XL650 with:
- optional electric casefeeder
- optional aluminum roller handle (standard ball handle also included)
- optional bullet tray
- optional electronic early warning low primer system
Manual
Lots of manuals & paperwork for the other stuff
4 bolts & associated hardware (washers, nuts etc) to mount machine to bench
XL650 spare parts kit
Dillon .223 carbide 3 die set
Dillon .223/222 caliber conversion kit
Dillon electronic powder check system (checks the powder fill for over/under charge)
Lyman 47th reloading handbook
Dillon Dial caliper
12 Blue Dillon trays
Bottle of case lube, about 75% full (used 1/4 of the bottle on thousands of cases)
Midway impact bullet puller
Dillon eliminator scale
Brass Dillon primer tray
Bag of old style lock rings (larger than the newer 1 inch rings)
.223 case gauge
4 Primer pick up tubes
Extra powder bars (1 small powder bar, 2 large powder bars
Dillon bench wrench
Extra slide & cam
Extra primer pick up tube ends (yellow for small primers)
5 extra powder check bars of various sizes for various caliber firearms
435 military style fmj projectiles with green tips (approx 62 grain projectiles, overall length varies due to non-precise manufacturing of these projectiles.  Some are very pointy and some are mostly pointed.  Overall lengths of these loaded rounds varied for me between about 2.240 - 2.260 approximately)
Approximately the same number of new un-primed brass .223 cases, no trimming needed.
2 extra powder measure failsafe rods (1 already on the machine)
Accurate Datapowder 2200 (yes, the hard to find good stuff).
I just opened this container of powder about a month ago.
There is just about 5lbs left (see photos) out of the 8lb jug.
Also will  throw in the 2 large ammo cans as seen in photos.
Dillon carries a lifetime warranty with the machine, regardless of who owns it.
The casefeeder however is out of warranty.
The casefeeder has some signs of use, the motor makes some buzzing noises sometimes, does not turn with as much power as it used to, and you have to tap the switch sometimes when it randomly stops feeding cases, but it works.
I toss about 3 large handfuls of brass into a large open cardboard box, laying on their side, and pump the case lube about twice, and then tumble the cases around in the box, and this seems to be the right amount of lube for the cases.
- do not cycle dry/un-lubed cases into the dies or you may break the shellplate (Dillon will send you a new shellplate for free if that happens, but you still don't want that to happen).
Machine piston likes to be lubed with motor oil.
Be sure to read instruction manual inside and out, and memorize the thing.
The more intimate you are with your instruction manual and machine, the more you will understand it.
I understood it blindfolded upside down, left to right.
You need to know what makes every part of it work.
The primer disc is extremely precise, and the smallest adjustment of the tiny allen wrench equals a substantial adjustment of the locator tab/arm.
Getting the primers to center exactly in the middle of the .223 case is the most challenging part of reloading, takes patience and many adjustments to get it just right.
I will also provide you with many more tips once you purchase this.
Feel free to email me with any other questions, or if you would like any other photos.

title: For Sale:  PPS 43-C Polish Pistol
postcontent:
Original Polish PPS-43C in a semi-auto version.  7.62x25 caliber, considered a pistol due to overall length.  .  The PPS-43C (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev SMG) was born as an answer to the need for a weapon that is more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, then in use by the Soviet Army.  The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews and mobile recon groups and paratroopers, so late in 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new more compact sub machine gun (SMG).  The designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942, and it was adopted under the designation of PPS-42.  The next year he refined the design, and this final model was designated as the PPS-43.  This model was manufactured in significant numbers (nearly two million PPS-43 weapons were manufactured between 1943 and 1946).  The PPS-43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. After WWII, it was widely exported to pro-Soviet regimes around the world, and widely copied.  This historical firearm has been re-designed to shoot from a closed bolt position.  The safety is located at the front of the trigger guard.  The receiver and barrel shroud are made from stamped steel.  The rear sight is an L-shaped flip type and is marked for 100 and 200 meters, the front sight is a fixed blade type.  The barrel is equipped with a simple muzzle brake.  This firearm is an ATF approved pistol.  The stock has no function and is permanently fixed in its folded position. 
 This pistol is manufactured at the famed Radom Plant in Poland. 
All parts and components are new and Polish made.
Comes with one (1) 35 round magazine, sling, and oil can.

title: For Sale:  Kahr CM9 with custom Multi-Holster
location: East side of Cleveland, Cleveland, Ohio
postcontent:
This is a great carry pistol that only has 250 rounds through it.  The manufacturer states there is a 200 round break in period for the CM9, so now you don't have to worry about spending the money on four boxes of ammo just to break it in. 

The initial 200 rounds were Winchester White Box ammo, and it cycled flawlessly.  I also ran another 50 rounds of various defense rounds through it to make sure there were no feed issues.  I ran 20 Hornady Critical Defense, 20 Spear Gold Dot, 10 Federal Hydrashok and all of it cycled perfectly.    

The CM9 is one of the slimmest and lightest 9mm's on the market, and the double recoil spring makes it surprisingly easy to manage muzzle flip.  Included is the original box, owners manual, and the six round magazine.  I'm selling it for 350, and I'll throw in a custom molded IWB Kydex Multi-Holster for free.  The holster currently retails for about 60 dollars, but if you tried to buy it through Multi-Holster it would probably be back ordered for 8-12 weeks.  It's a comfortable, streamlined holster with good retention.
